TextEquiv.Unicode: the forbidding of meates is a doctrine
of devils. Neither needeth anie man
here to tell us any whit of the Tacians
and Encratites: for they did flaunder
the good creatures of God. Paul spea
keth of them, who, although they doe
not utterly condeme meate and ma
riage doe yet notwithstanding forbid
the use of meate.
Furthermore we doe not read that
any lawes were ordeyned in that age
which followeth next after the prea
ching of the Apostles, which did com
maund and prescribe any time and or
der of fasting, or choise of meates. I
will rehearse unto you (dearely belo
ved) the wordes of Irenaeus the mar
tyre, which in the Ecclesiasticall histo
rie of Eusebius, are to be found worde
for worde as they are here set downe.
The ocntroversie is not onely tou
ching Easter day, but also touching
the manner of fasting. For some doe
thinke that the fast ought to be kept
but one day onely, other two, other
more, and some whoale 4.0 dayes, so
that counting the houres of the night
and day, they make a day. Which dif
ference of observing the times, is not
nowe first of all in our age begon, but
was brought in a greate while agoe (as
I suppose) of them which did not sim
ply keepe that, which was taught from
the beginning, but eyther by negli
gence or unskilfulnesse fell afterwarde
into a worser use and custome. And
yet notwithstanding, all these though
they jarred in the observation of times,
were neverthelesse and are agreea
ble with us, neyther hath the discorde
about fasting, broake our concorde in
faith. Thus much Irenaeus. Moreo
ver, Socrates Constantinopolitanus in
the 9. booke and 18. Chapter of his tri
partite historie witnesseth, that about
the yeare of our Lorde 453. in the

Which dif ference of observing the times, is not nowe first of all in our age begon, but was brought in a greate while agoe (as I suppose) of them which did not sim ply keepe that, which was taught from the beginning, but eyther by negli gence or unskilfulnesse fell afterwarde into a worser use and custome. And yet notwithstanding, all these though they jarred in the observation of times, were neverthelesse and are agreea ble with us, neyther hath the discorde about fasting, broake our concorde in faith. Thus much Irenaeus. Moreo ver, Socrates Constantinopolitanus in the 9. booke and 18. Chapter of his tri partite historie witnesseth, that about the yeare of our Lorde 453. in the
reigne of Theodosius the younger, the
same diversitie was in the Church,
and setteth it downe in these wordes
following: Furthermore they have
not the same kinde of abstinence from
meate: For some doe altogether ab
steine from living creatures: some a
mong living creatures doe eate fishe
onely: some with fish doe feede on
soules also, saying, that they (as Moses
saith) have their substaunce of water:
Some are knowne to absteine from
Hearbes and egges: some doe feede of
drie breade onely: some not so much
as that: some fasting nine houres, doe
then without difference use any kinde
of meate: and innumerable customes
are found among sundrie men. Nowe
the verie same Socrates shewing his
opinion upon that diversitie doth say:
And for because no auncient writing
is found touching this thing, I thinke
that the Apostles lest it free to everie
mans judgement, taht everie one may
worke, not by feare or necessitie, the
thing that is good. Thus farre So
crates. The fastes of Christians ther
fore ought to be free and not bound to
lawes. Apollinus, a certaine aunci
ent and Ecclesiasticall writer dispu
ting against Montanus the heretique
saieth: This is hee which taught that
marriages are undone, and which first
of all hath appointed lawes for men to
fast by. And verily to give about to
set downe to all men, and nations, one
manner of fasting in one appointed
time, one prescribed order, and choice
of meate is a meere follie, & a braine
sicke kinde of madnesse, For according
to the choice of ayre, so are mens bo
dies of sundrie temperatures, and one
kinde of meate doth not stirre men of
sundrie complexions, to one kinde of
affection. The most godly way there
fore, & profitable order for the Church
